Network Scan Using Nmap.
Target: 192.168.1.0/24
Scan date: 2025-10-20
Executive Summary:
A TCP SYN service discovery and version scan was performed against the local
subnet 192.168.1.0/24 to identify active hosts, open TCP ports and the services
running on them. Nmap detected 5 hosts up with services such as FTP, SSH, DNS,
HTTP(S), SMB and AJP. Several hosts had filtered ports indicating firewalling. The
purpose of this report is to document service exposure and identify potential security
risks.
2. Scope & commands used:
Scope: 192.168.1.0/24 (local network)
Primary commands used:
Host discovery / SYN scan:
sudo nmap -sS 192.168.1.0/24
Service/version detection (used for follow-up):
sudo nmap -sS -sV 192.168.1.0/24
Optional packet capture for deeper analysis:
sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -w capture.pcap (open capture.pcap in Wireshark)

4. Common services observed:
 FTP (21/tcp) - file transfer; typically unencrypted and may allow anonymous
access.
 SSH (22/tcp) - secure remote shell (OpenSSH/Dropbear).
 DNS (53/tcp) - dnsmasq; DNS service (may permit zone transfers if
misconfigured).
 HTTP/HTTPS (80/443) - web admin panel or router UI; tcpwrapped indicates
banner blocking or proxy.
 SMB / MSRPC (135/139/445) - Windows file/printer sharing and RPC services.
High-value for info and lateral movement.
 AJP (8009/tcp) - Tomcat AJP connector; historically associated with Ghostcat
(CVE-2020-1938) if exposed.
4. Potential security risks & priority:
 SMB exposed on 192.168.1.2 (135/139/445) — High priority. Exposed SMB can
allow share enumeration, weak-auth access, or be used for lateral movement. Action:
check for anonymous shares, enforce strong ACLs, apply Windows updates, and
restrict SMB to trusted hosts only.
FTP on 192.168.1.1 (21) — Medium. Plaintext credentials possible. Action: disable
anonymous FTP, migrate to SFTP/FTPS if needed, and restrict access.
 AJP on 192.168.1.5 (8009 filtered) — Medium. If AJP is exposed and Tomcat is
unpatched, Ghostcat can allow file read. Action: verify Tomcat version, restrict AJP
connector to localhost or firewall it, or disable if unused.
 Web admin on router (80/443 tcpwrapped) — Medium. tcpwrapped could be a
protective wrapper or proxy. Action: access admin page from browser on local
machine, check default creds, update firmware, disable remote admin or restrict by IP.
 Hosts with filtered ports (23, 1037) — Low/Info. May indicate firewalling;
confirm whether intentional.
Packet Capture Analysis Using Wireshark
Objective:
Capture and inspect packet-level traffic to validate the behavior of the TCP SYN scan
performed from the scanning host (192.168.1.9) against hosts in the
192.168.1.0/24 subnet.
Tool:
Wireshark on Kali Linux.
Procedure (summary):
1. Capture was performed on interface eth0 while running the scan from 192.168.1.9.
2. Wireshark display filter tcp.flags.syn == 1 && tcp.flags.ack == 0 was
applied to isolate initial SYN probes sent by the scanner.
3. Packets were inspected to confirm SYN probes, and corresponding target
responses (SYN+ACK or RST) were reviewed in follow-up filters.
Evidence:
Wireshark analysis.png
Figure: SYN probes captured from 192.168.1.9 to multiple targets/ports (filter:
tcp.flags.syn==1 && tcp.flags.ack==0) - confirms scan traffic and probe destinations.
Observation (from screenshot)
The screenshot shows many TCP SYN packets with source IP 192.168.1.9 (the
scanner) and multiple destination IPs in the local subnet (examples visible: 192.168.1.1,
192.168.1.2, 192.168.1.6).
Destination ports in the visible samples include 143 (IMAP), 443 (HTTPS), 80
(HTTP), 21 (FTP), 8080 (HTTP-alt), 23 (Telnet), 993 (IMAPS), 995 (POP3S) and
several ephemeral ports (e.g., 1025).
The packet list shows each probe as [SYN] Seq=0 with Len=0 — characteristic of a
TCP SYN scan (nmap -sS).
These SYN probes are the scanning requests; the presence (or absence) of responses
(SYN+ACK for open, RST for closed, or no response for filtered) in the full capture
corroborates the port states reported by Nmap.
Interpretation
The capture confirms that Nmap performed SYN probes from 192.168.1.9 to multiple
hosts/ports.
Ports that generated SYN+ACK responses in the capture should be considered open,
ports that generated RST closed, and ports with no reply filtered (likely by firewall).
The variety of destination ports indicates Nmap probed both common service ports
(HTTP/HTTPS/FTP/IMAP/SMB-related ports elsewhere in the scan) and alternative
web or service ports (8080, 8888, etc.).
Conclusion
The Wireshark packet capture provides packet-level confirmation of the TCP SYN
scan performed from 192.168.1.9. The capture validates that Nmap’s probes targeted
the same hosts and ports listed in the Findings section, and the recorded
SYN/SYN+ACK/RST patterns support the open/closed/filtered port determinations
reported by Nmap.
